{"key":"processedPost-16413084","value":{"id":16413084,"first":16400345,"last":16485676,"when":1340286833,"utime":"06/21/12 04:53 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Terry M said:</strong><br />Question for RR:<br />Can the Fischer hygrometers be left in a high humidity environment (95%) all the time, or should they just be put in for 5 minutes or so to get a reading in order to protect them and extend their lives?</blockquote><br />I haven't removed either of mine from the grow room since day one.&nbsp; We spray twice daily with a hose, and while we try to avoid direct high pressure spray on the hygrometers, plenty of water splashes directly on the units every time with no harm. <br />For most commercial mushrooms, you don't really want to maintain a very high humidity all the time.&nbsp; Spray well, which is going to raise the humidity up to 98% or so, and then let it drop to 75%(or lower if growing strictly shiitake) and then spray again.&nbsp; This benefits whatever you're growing and as an added benefit, lets the hygrometer dry out inside and&nbsp; keeps the mechanism constantly moving.<br />RR"}}